# Clean Architecture

All code MUST be organized in three layers with dependencies pointing inward only.

```
infrastructure  -->  application  -->  domain
(outer)              (middle)          (inner)
```

## Layers

### `domain/`

The core. Pure business logic, zero external dependencies.

- Entities, value objects, domain events, business rules
- NEVER imports from `application/` or `infrastructure/`
- No framework code, no database code, no I/O
- Must be testable in complete isolation

### `application/` (or `use-cases/`)

Orchestration layer. Coordinates domain objects to fulfill use cases.

- Depends only on `domain/`
- Defines **ports** (interfaces/abstractions) that infrastructure must implement
- Contains use case handlers, application services, DTOs
- No concrete I/O — all external access goes through ports

### `infrastructure/`

Adapters to the outside world. Implements the ports defined by application.

- Database repositories, HTTP clients, message queues, file system access
- Framework configuration, controllers, routes
- UI components (frontend) live here too — they are adapters
- This is the ONLY layer allowed to depend on external libraries and frameworks

## Recommended folder structure

Adapt to the stack, but keep the layering:

```
src/
  domain/
    entities/
    value-objects/
    errors/
  application/
    use-cases/
    ports/
    dtos/
  infrastructure/
    persistence/
    http/
    config/
```

## The golden rule

**Domain NEVER imports from infrastructure.** If you need an external resource in the domain, define a port (interface) in `application/` and implement it in `infrastructure/`.
